The data sets presented previously indicate that the response to RH may be one that increases, decreases, remains unchanged, or even presents a maxima. These variations in responses have posed difficulties when it comes to modeling, but the key to accurately modeling these RH effects lies in defining a model composed of components, each of which may rise or decrease in response to RH. Since the RH effect is generally understood to be mainly a function of both thymine dimers and spore photoproducts, it can be modeled as two components that will sum to produce an overall response curve. In fact, there are probably additional components, but as a first order model, if we assume that the RH effect is due only to these two factors, the combined equation for the rate constant can be written as follows:(3.7)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
